EMA update iterates over `base_model.state_dict()` every training step. Building a full state_dict each step adds avoidable overhead and includes tensors that may not need EMA (or may be buffers). Consider precomputing a list of parameters/buffers to track (e.g., named_parameters + named_buffers) and updating those directly, which avoids reconstructing the dict each step and makes it explicit what EMA applies to.
```suggestion
            # Lazily build and cache the list of tensors tracked by EMA to avoid
            # reconstructing base_model.state_dict() on every training step.
            if not hasattr(base_model, "_ema_tracked_tensors"):
                ema_tracked = []
                # Track parameters that have corresponding EMA entries.
                for name, param in base_model.named_parameters():
                    if name in ema_state:
                        ema_tracked.append((name, param))
                # Optionally track buffers as well, if they are present in ema_state.
                for name, buf in base_model.named_buffers():
                    if name in ema_state:
                        ema_tracked.append((name, buf))
                base_model._ema_tracked_tensors = ema_tracked
